    pearls: ["Multimodal analgesia targets different pain pathways: opioids (central), NSAIDs (peripheral), gabapentinoids (neuropathic), local anesthetics (peripheral nerve)", "PCA pump safety: only the patient should press the button; family/nurse activation causes oversedation", "Naloxone reversal: dilute 0.4 mg in 10 mL NS, give 0.5 mL every 2 minutes titrating to respiratory rate; avoid full reversal in opioid-tolerant patients", "Respiratory depression is the most dangerous opioid side effect; sedation precedes respiratory depression", "Equianalgesic dosing is essential when converting between opioids to prevent under- or over-dosing"],
    lifespan: { title: "Opioid Considerations Across the Lifespan", content: "Neonates have immature hepatic metabolism and reduced protein binding, requiring lower weight-based opioid doses. Elderly patients have decreased renal clearance and increased sensitivity to CNS depressants; start low and titrate slowly. Pregnant patients require careful opioid management to prevent neonatal abstinence syndrome." },
